Perimeter Defense - Email Security > [T4]: Email reconnaissance: How attackers gather intel


Attackers perform some reconnaissance before launching an email attack to increase the odds of a successful compromise. It helps them understand the target organization's security posture and find possible entry points. A typical reconnaissance activity involves gathering multiple solicited emails from a company to determine how email addresses are formatted and existing email security controls.


There are multiple ways attackers can make the target company send them emails. One way is to submit the contact us form on the companys website, which will send an automated email confirming the receipt of the request as in the following example:

 

Figure - zoom in

 

This single email provides attackers with important information such as:

  1. The domain that's used to send and receive emails. Usually, this is the same website domain, but I have seen organizations that use different domains. For example, the website is xyz.com, and the mail domain is mail.xyz.com or xyz.net.
  2. Email address format. For example, if a company user's first and last name is John Smith, the company can use the following naming convention formats: john.smith@xyz.com', smith.john@xyz.com', j.smith@xyz.com', jsmith@xyz.com', smith.j@xyz.com' and smithj@xyz.com'.
  3. Email headers can reveal critical information about the network layout and what devices the mail travels through inside the target network. In the following example, the mail headers showed that the email traveled through two internal exchange servers before reaching the mail gateway that forwarded it to Google mail servers. The mail gateway is IronPort, a popular email security appliance.

 

Figure - zoom in


This is a wealth of information for attackers. Knowing what type of mail security appliance the target company has, makes it easy to find out about available/missing protection mechanisms and possible ways to make a malicious email land in the users inbox.  Google mail headers analyzer is a decent service we can use to analyze mail headers. If you prefer not to use a cloud option, you can deploy your local version of the free, open-source tool we developed, Email Header Analyzer.

 

Figure - zoom in


Another way to make the target company send emails is by collecting a list of leaked email addresses and sending bulk messages hoping to receive out-of-office notifications. Many times, organizations' business emails were leaked intentionally and unintentionally.

Many free tools can automate the search process of leaked email addresses, such as EmailHarvester. It asks for a domain name and tries to retrieve leaked email addresses for that domain using search engines. 

SOC analysts should configure the outgoing mail gateway -the last hop before leaving the internal network- to strip all internal mail headers to prevent outgoing emails from leaking important information.

 

Almost all Secure Email Gateways offer to strip email headers for incoming and outgoing mail traffic. To do so, we need the header name and then configure the SEG to strip that header. The previous example's header that disclosed the Exchange server name was Message-ID. So, we can configure the SEG to strip that header as in the following screenshot.

To get this view, browse to Mail policies->Outgoing content filters-> add filter->add action.

 

Figure - zoom in

 

Its also vital to select decoy names for servers and network devices. Instead of setting the hostname of the SEG to IronPort, we can make it something irrelevant. Organizations should have a standard naming convention that maintains privacy. Some organizations name servers after colors (i.e., 01-red), and some use individual names (i.e., Alex, Johnetc.).
